<div id="comment_65288051" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_65288051" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65288051" name="comment_link_65288051" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23658805&amp;cid=65288051" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65288051)" >Practicality of 8k for most uses?</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65288051" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65288051); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~nightflameauto">nightflameauto</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~nightflameauto">( 6607976 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65288051">		
		on Monday April 07, 2025 @05:47PM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23658805&amp;cid=65288051">#65288051</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65288051"><p>Is there a practical home-use for an 8k monitor/TV? I'm all for the more is more philosophy, but I think at home sizes there's a point of diminishing returns that, if we haven't crossed it, we've got to be approaching. I have a 65" 4k TV that I sit only about 8 feet away from, and I honestly don't know how much more crisp that image needs to get. And I'm not sure most homes have room for something bigger. I suppose I *COULD* go up to 75" if I wanted to start soaking up the walkway around the living room, but how far are we gonna push the "more pixels" thing?</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65288051">
